@node "doc_introduction" "Introduction"
DreamTerm is basic terminal program with bunch of usual features.

@{u} Features @{uu}

 o Hardware screen & serial for those who want maximum speed.
 o Xpr 2.0, 2.001 and external support, no internal protocols at all.
 o XEm 2.0 support for possibility to add new emulations without upgrading
   main file.
 o Internal Ansi/VT102 emulation for use with bbs systems, very fast.
 o Internal hex dump emulation, totally useless.
 o Prescroll to speedup scrolling.
 o Phonebook entry count limited only by available memory.
 o Possibility to crypt phonebook using xpk librarary.
 o Most options can be configured individually for every phonebook entry.
 o Profile for sharing options between different phonebook entries.
 o Uses MUI for windows allowing user (you!) to configure interface look.
 o Console can use any fixed size font.
 o Screenmode support.
 o Real time input/output conversion.
 o Configurable graphical toolbar.
 o Online help.
 o Locales for english and finnish

@{u} Missing features @{uu}

DreamTerm don't have script language as I oppose that kind of thing in simple
terminals, I feel that if somebody need scripts and can write them they also
can write them in C.

@{u} The concepts behind user interface @{uu}

DreamTerm uses a object-oriented approach to provide a flexible and extendable
system. This approach will hopefully made it possible to enhance several
DreamTerm features in future.

An object is a collection of data which describes its features. Each object
has a name and a type. You can create as many objects of each type as you
want, but the name of each object has to be unique, because it is used as a
reference to this object.

Currently there are five different types of objects: Charset, Protocol, XEm,
Toolbar, Phonebook Entry. The first four of them are basic objects; that means
they don't reference other objects. They provide data or services for the
complex objects.

The last object type is complex object; that means it reference simple objects
and rely on them to get access to data or services. The reference is done by
name, and if no simple object with this name exists, the complex object will
ignore it or use hardcoded default. Note that this may reduce the
functionality of the complex object, e.g. an Protocol object is needed to do
data transfer.

However as you will notice by using DreamTerm this object concept is not fully
used in every part, this is mainly due my limited knowledge of object
orientated programming and also the fact that I wasn't thinking all the things
as throughly in the beginning as I should have. Oh, and you may notice that
ToolManager documentation has slightly same introduction how object-oriented
approach works. It was explained so well that I decided to copy it. :)
@endnode

@node "doc_requirements" "Power is everything and money is essential"
DreamTerm requires little bit more from your machine than other terminal
programs, reason is simply that I want to use new features found from
KickStart 3.0. As for using MUI I must say that easiness is number 1 reason,
no other system offers anything like it in respect of user friendliness and
configurability. This fortunately do not mean that you need fast processor and
gigabytes of memory, though harddrive is essential as there is no though given
for floppy disk usage. Anyway I feel that required software is not much, heck
you can still use old A500 almost without problems.

This is minimal configuration:

 Amiga A500-A4000T 
 KickStart 3.0
 Magic User Interface 3.3
 Central Processing Unit 68000
 1MB of memory.

One little requirement is also that you should use fixed width font when
reading this guide, otherwise some parts will look ugly.
@endnode

