@node "help_base_general_load" "Load"
This will discard current entries and load new file, however those entries
which are currently in use are not discarded.
@endnode

@node "help_base_general_save" "Save"
This will save whole list.
@endnode

@node "help_base_general_append" "Append"
This will append file to current list, if file contains entries which have
same name as in current list then current list entry will stay.
@endnode

@node "help_base_general_save_selecte" "Save selected"
This will save selected entry.
@endnode

@node "help_base_general_close" "Close"
This will close window.
@endnode

@node "help_base_general_lv" "Listview"
Listview is used to select entry to edit or show, if there is string gadget
immediately below it then you can edit entrys name using it, to actually
change it you must press return in string gadget, tab cycle is not enough!
Remember that there must be different name for every entry, so if nothing
happens then there is either same name in list or memory shortage. Note also
that this affects new entry creation too, so do not use '-- NEW --' name for
entry as it is internally used by DreamTerm.
@endnode

@node "help_base_general_add" "Add"
This will create new entry named '-- NEW --' in your list, of course if there
is already entry with same name this won't do anything.
@endnode

@node "help_base_general_delete" "Delete"
This will delete entry from list, note that phonebook entries use name to
identify which charset/protocol etc. entry to use so deleting may force some
of them to use default. However those phonebook entries will remember the name
which they were using so if you later on create some 'resource' entry with
same name they will again start to use it.
@endnode

@node "help_entry" "PhoneBook entry, profile and current settings"

                                   @{"   BBS   " link "help_bbs" 0}
                                   @{" Serial  " link "help_serial" 0}
                                   @{" Screen  " link "help_screen" 0}
                                   @{"Transfer " link "help_transfer" 0}
                                   @{"Emulation" link "help_emulation" 0}
                                   @{"Keyboard " link "help_keyboard" 0}
                                   @{"  Modem  " link "help_modem" 0}

Due the fact that DreamTerm allows changing almost every individual setting in
every phonebook entry this window is used for multiple purposes. First it can
be used to change current settings if you don't want to use menu 'shortcuts'.
It is also used to change different profiles and finally for normal Phonebook
entry editing. Gadget actions are always same only 'Set pick' and 'Clear pick'
will act differently.

Note that opening this window can take some time if @{"Dispose window objects" link "menu_project_dispose window ob" 0} is
on. You always edit copied values, changes are updated only when you press OK
button, cancel or close window will discard everything.

Below is explanation about differences between modes.

@{u} Current settings @{uu}

In this mode you can change all current settings at once, however if current
settings are change during editing no changes are updated for this window.
Current settings changing will happen if you use menus or dial succesfully to
some system.

Notes:

Set pick & Clear pick are disabled.

@{u} Profile @{uu}

In this mode you edit @{"profile" link "doc_terminology" 0}. All settings which are 'profiled' in phonebook
entries will pick their values from here. These settings are also use when you
create totally new phonebook entry. Settings which appear 'ghosted' here when
set pick is on will be 'ghosted' also in newly created entry. Note currently
there is only one profile but I plan to 'upgrade' DreamTerm so that you can
have as many profiles as you want. It will be real mess for you. :P

Notes:

 Set pick    - option is placed to default pick from profile state.
 Clear pick  - option is placed to default pick from local state.

@{u} Creating/Editing entry @{uu}

Options which are copied from profile table will appear 'ghosted' and you
cannot edit them. Remember that every option which is picked from profile can
be changed only from that profile. Example: you have set of phonebook entries
which all pick dte from profile (ghosted), now if you change dte in profile
then all those entries will change too! (I hope you understand the idea)

Notes:

 Set pick    - option will be copied from profile.
 Clear pick  - option will be copied from local (here).

@{u} Good to know @{uu}

When you use Set/Clear pick then you must always change gadget state in order
something to happen, for example is not enough to press return in string
gadget you must write to it! Option will always go to disabled state when you
change it to desired state. (Well... option == setting:^) This is required
because MUI will not tell anything to program if gadget state do not change.
@endnode

@node "help_bbs" "Entry"

                    @{"                  BBS                  " link "help_serial" 0}

                    @{"Name      " link "help_bbs_name" 0} ----------------------------
                    @{"Phone     " link "help_bbs_phone" 0} @{"---" link "help_bbs_phone number prefix" 0} ------------------------
                    @{"Password  " link "help_bbs_password" 0} ----------------------------
                    @{"Comment   " link "help_bbs_comment" 0} ----------------------------
                    @{"Logfile   " link "help_bbs_logfile" 0} ----------------------------
                    @{"Call      " link "help_bbs_call" 0} ----- @{"Wait between dials" link "help_bbs_wait between dials" 0} ---
                    @{"Minute    " link "help_bbs_minute" 0} ----- @{"Wait dialing      " link "help_wait dialing" 0} ---

                    @{"X" link "help_bbs_log calls" 0} Log calls
@endnode

@node "help_bbs_name" "Entry window: Name"
@next "help_bbs_phone"
@prev "help_bbs"
System name, can be anything and has no other meaning than to tell you what
system this entry refers to.
@endnode

@node "help_bbs_phone" "Entry window: Phone number"
First string is @{"prefix" link "help_bbs_phone number prefix" 0} which is added in front of phonenumber when dialing.
Second string is actual phonenumber, use | to separate numbers if there is
more  than one number to dial. These are also the numbers which are compared
against droplist when adding new entry.

Examples:

 prefix 101 number 555-666|555-555 : first dialing string is 101 555-666 and
                                     second is 101 555-555.

 prefix     number 555-666|555-555 : first dialing string is 555-666 and
                                     second is 555-555.
@endnode

@node "help_bbs_phone number prefix" "Entry window: Phone number prefix"
In dialing this prefix is added in front of normal @{"phone number" link "help_bbs_phone" 0}. Idea behind
this is to help finnish users who have 3 different long distance companies. In
order this to work you must put prefix to profile state (ghosted) in entries
which are long distance calls. If you do so you can quickly change company
using menu @{"Profile phone prefix" link "menu_project_profile phone pre" 0}. For short distance calls you must leave
prefix empty and not in profile state.
@endnode

@node "help_bbs_password" "Password"
System password, handy as you propably don't want to remember every single
password which you use in different systems. This string can be sent using
menu @{"send current password" link "menu_phonebook_send current pa" 0}. If you use this you should also use
@{"phonebook crypting" link "menu_project_phonebook cryptin" 0} as it is very easy to pretend to be you if somebody steals
your phonebook.
@endnode

@node "help_bbs_comment" "Comment"
Some comment which you want to see during dialing.
@endnode

@node "help_bbs_logfile" "Logfile"
Specify here where you want logfile to be written, without path current
directory is used. You must also set @{"log calls" link "help_bbs_log calls" 0} on as this only tells which
logfile to use.
@endnode

@node "help_bbs_call" "Call"
How much call costs.
@endnode

@node "help_bbs_minute" "Minute    "
How much one minute in online costs.
@endnode

@node "help_bbs_wait between dials" "Wait between dials"
Defines in seconds how long to wait between dials in this entry.
@endnode

@node "help_bbs_wait dialing" "Wait dialing"
Maximum time to wait in seconds current dial try to succeed.
@endnode

@node "help_bbs_log calls" "Log calls"
Set this on to log calls to @{"logfile" link "help_bbs_logfile" 0}, you should put logfile to pick from
profile state if you want all calls to be logged in one file. You need 7-wire
serial cable and correctly setted modem which reports carrier signal in order
this to work. After you have been disconnected from system some information
will be saved, this includes start time, stop time, system name, called
phonenumber, overruns, elapsed time in seconds, avr. txd speed, avr. rxd
speed, how many characters were sent and how many characters were received.
Overruns and avr. txd/rxd time will be zero if other than hardware serial is
used

Format is:

 day dd-mmm-yy hh:mm:ss day dd-mmm-yy hh:mm:ss (starttime, stoptime)
 %s         (system name)
 %s         (called phonenumber)
 %-5ld %ld  (overruns, elapsed time in seconds)
 %-5ld %ld  (avr. txd speed, sent bytes)
 %-5ld %ld  (avr. rxd speed, received bytes)
 \n

Example:

 Fri 01-Jan-95 12:00:00 Fri 01-Jan-95 12:00:10
 BatMUD online
 555 12345678
 0     10
 32    31343
 100   540409
@endnode

@node "help_serial" "Serial"

                    @{"                Serial                 " link "help_screen" 0}

                    @{"DTE       " link "help_serial_dte" 0} ----------------------------
                    @{"Databits  " link "help_serial_databits" 0} ----------------------------
                    @{"Stopbits  " link "help_serial_stopbits" 0} ----------------------------
                    @{"Parity    " link "help_serial_parity" 0} ----------------------------
                    @{"Duplex    " link "help_serial_duplex" 0} ----------------------------
                    @{"Flow      " link "help_serial_flow" 0} ----------------------------
                    @{"Device  " link "help_serial_device" 0} @{"X" link "help_serial_device" 0} ------- @{"X" link "help_serial_hardware serial" 0} @{"Hardware serial   " link "help_serial_hardware serial" 0}
                    @{"Unit    " link "help_serial_unit" 0} ========= @{"X" link "help_serial_fixed_dte_rate" 0} @{"Fixed DTE rate    " link "help_serial_fixed_dte_rate" 0}
                    @{"Buffer  " link "help_serial_buffer" 0} ========= @{"X" link "help_serial_drop_dtr_to_hangup" 0} @{"Drop DTR on hangup" link "help_serial_drop_dtr_to_hangup" 0}
                                       @{"X" link "help_serial_shared_serial" 0} @{"Shared serial     " link "help_serial_shared_serial" 0}
@endnode

@node "help_serial_dte" "DTE rate"
What DTE speed to use, you can choose from predefined set.

If you use standard Amiga serial hardware you should always use lowest
practical value, for v32bis modems dte rate 38400 is just fine and you can use
it even with v.34 modems if you mainly do packed file transfers.

Anyway, if you wanna test which is highest working dte you can use hardware
serial and see if there is overruns when modem is sending data at maximum
speed to Amiga. If your modem has some test commands (AT&T8) you can try to to
use it, or if not then just download some null-ascii file from BBS  (many of
them have test files for cps freaks:-). Note that changing screen modes,
moving vbr to fast etc. may give different results, and remember that normal
serial.device may not work at same speed as customized @{"hardware serial" link "help_serial_hardware serial" 0} option.
@endnode

@node "help_serial_databits" "Databits"
How many bits in character, currently always 8.
@endnode

@node "help_serial_stopbits" "Stopbits"
How many stopbits between databits, currently always 1.
@endnode

@node "help_serial_parity" "Parity"
Parity, currently always none.
@endnode

@node "help_serial_duplex" "Duplex"

 Full duplex - Typed characters are not echoed to console.

 Half duplex - Typed characters are echoed to console.
@endnode

@node "help_serial_flow" "Flow"
Which flow control type to use, currently always RTS/CTS.
@endnode

@node "help_serial_device" "Device"
Which device to use, note that device is not used when hardware serial option
is on.
@endnode

@node "help_serial_buffer" "Buffer"
Serial buffer size, should be large enough to hold couple of seconds incoming
data at maximum speed.
@endnode

@node "help_serial_unit" "Unit"
Which unit to use from device (0-255), normally you should use 0 but if using
shared serial then it might be good idea to use 1 or bigger.
@endnode

@node "help_serial_hardware serial" "Hardware serial"
Use custom serial routines for internal serial port, they are faster and
should allow a bit higher dte rate without overrun errors. Also some extra
information is available when they are in use, like overrun count and cps
rate. However they are not a miracle cure for slow machine and even that they
allocate port using misc.resource and use legal way to allocate serial
interrupts they can crash machine if internal port is not available or those
serial interrupts are used by some exotic hardware. Naturally you should not
use this option if you have any kind of serial card but instead use
manufacturer supplied replacement for serial.device. Also only 8N1 is
supported by this option.

Note that serial.device, BaudBandit.device and artser.device are removed from
memory when you set this option on, this is due the fact that they allocate
misc.resource (serial port) when they are in memory and thus this option would
otherwise fail. If you have used other device you must use 'avail flush'
cli-command to remove the from memory.
@endnode

@node "help_serial_fixed_dte_rate" "X"
DTE rate is always what you have defined, currently always used. In dark age
of modem usage it was sometimes useful to change DTE rate to match what was
printed in connect string, nowadays it is complete useless.
@endnode

@node "help_serial_drop_dtr_to_hangup" "X"
Hangup dropping dtr instead sending ~+~+~+~ATH\r, your modem must be setted to
react dtr dropping.
@endnode

@node "help_serial_shared_serial" "X"
Open device in shared mode, makes possible two programs to use serial port at
same time. Is mainly useful when you plan to use external protocols and want
modem to hangup if DTR is dropped.
@endnode

@node "help_screen" "Screen"

              @{"                      Screen                      " link "help_transfer" 0}

              +--+ @{"X" link "help_screen_borderblank" 0} @{"BorderBlank          " link "help_screen_borderblank" 0} @{"X" link "help_screen_hardware_screen" 0} @{"Hardware screen    " link "help_screen_hardware_screen" 0}
              |@{"  " link "help_screen_lv" 0}| @{"X" link "help_screen_keep_workbench_col" 0} @{"Keep workbench colors" link "help_screen_keep_workbench_col" 0} @{"X" link "help_screen_enable_aga_bandwit" 0} @{"Enable AGA bandwith" link "help_screen_enable_aga_bandwit" 0}
              |  | @{"X" link "help_screen_rts_blit" 0} @{"RTS blit             " link "help_screen_rts_blit" 0} @{"X" link "help_screen_automatic_rxd_popu" 0} @{"Automatix RXD popup" link "help_screen_automatic_rxd_popu" 0}
              |  | @{"Status" link "help_screen_status" 0} --------------------------------------
              |  | @{"Format" link "help_screen_format" 0} --------------------------------------
              +--+ @{"Pubscreen" link "help_screen_pubscreen" 0} ------------- @{"X" link "help_screen_use public screen" 0} @{"Use public screen  " link "help_screen_use public screen" 0}
              @{"        Screen mode         " link "help_screen_screen mode" 0} @{"X" link "help_screen_force" 0} @{"Force size         " link "help_screen_force" 0}
              @{"Columns" link "help_screen_columns" 0} ==========================================
              @{"Lines  " link "help_screen_lines" 0} ==========================================
              @{"H-Lines" link "help_screen_h-lines" 0} ==========================================
@endnode

@node "help_screen_lv" ""
Which character set to use.
@endnode

@node "help_screen_borderblank" "BorderBlank"
Set borderblank on, this is genlock option and normally will make your borders
to be black.
@endnode

@node "help_screen_keep_workbench_col" "Keep workbench colors"
Normally DreamTerm uses first 8-16 pens from custom screen to optimize
scrolling and allow perfect colors for emulation, however if you use screen
with same amount of colors it will propably make windows etc. look little bit
strange. Setting this option you tell that window colors are more important
than perfect emulation colors, this also prevents relocating of system pens
and thus allow crap programs look right when opened in DreamTerm's public
screen.

As downside you may get ugly borders depending you background color, though if
background color is black you can try @{"BorderBlank" link "help_screen_borderblank" 0} option. Scrolling is also
affected and can be little bit slower and may even flicker. So generally best
result is gained using at least 32 color screen and leaving this option off.
@endnode

@node "help_screen_rts_blit" "RTS blit"
Drop RTS when doing large blits in console, in theory if your blitter
operations block CPU this would prevent overruns.
@endnode

@node "help_screen_hardware_screen" "Hardware screen"
Use custom made "hardware" screen instead of system friendly and all ways
better system one. You are restricted for 80x(24-32) PAL screen and 8x8 font.
As you can quess it is opened using hardware directly and thus is not very
friendly to use nor work with Amigas which don't have ECS/AGA chipset. Note
that hardware screen depth is get from screenmode requester, though it will
open at 16 colors if there is bigger value in requester.

If you have VGA monitor be careful not to switch this on as it will not sync
with your monitor.

Actually this is very useless option but as it is done there is no reason to
remove it.
@endnode

@node "help_screen_enable_aga_bandwit" "Enable AGA bandwith"
If you're using hardware screen and you have AGA chipset set this on to allow
larger bandwith to chip memory. In practise you must have AGA chipset and this
option on to use 16 color screen.
@endnode

@node "help_screen_automatic_rxd_popu" "Automatix RXD popup"
Pop hardware screen to front when receiving chars from serial.
@endnode

@node "help_screen_status" "Status"
Status type, currently only line is finished.
@endnode

@node "help_screen_format" "Format"
This is format string for status line, you can use all @{"string codes" link "doc_string commands" 0} in it.
@endnode

@node "help_screen_screen mode" "Screen mode"
Which screenmode to use, also some other characterist can changed here like
autoscroll, overscan type and pixel width/height which is used with @{"Force" link "help_screen_force" 0}
@{"screenreq's size" link "help_screen_force" 0} option.

If your hardware supports more than 16 colors I advice to use at least 32
colors, it has very little effect on console speed/scrolling and MUI windows
etc. will look much better. I have no info if graphics cards work with
DreamTerm but if they do then you propably should use 256 colors as they
mostly use chunky graphics and bitmap emulation will slow screen refresh.
@endnode

@node "help_screen_columns" "Columns"
How many characters should be visible in one console line, value between 1-256
can be chosen. However be careful as minimal values may lead to use so small
screen that you cannot open windows in it.

Note: In current settings this will always change to reflect right size if you
resize window in public screen, use Force screenreq's size option in custom
screen or for some other reason console width cannot be same as requested.
@endnode

@node "help_screen_lines" "Lines  "
How many lines should be visible in console, value between 1-256 can be
chosen. However be careful as minimal values may lead to use so small screen
that you cannot open windows in it.

Note: In current settings this will always change to reflect right size if you
resize window in public screen, use Force screenreq's size option in custom
screen or for some other reason console height cannot be same as requested.
@endnode

@node "help_screen_h-lines" "H-Lines"
How many lines should be visible in hardware screen, value between 24-32 can
be chosen.
@endnode

@node "help_screen_pubscreen" "Public screen name"
Which public screen to use, you must set @{"use public screen" link "help_screen_use public screen" 0} in order console to
open defined screen.
@endnode

@node "help_screen_use public screen" ""
Open console to defined public screen, if console cannot be opened to defined
screen then Workbench is used and if that fails then DreamTerm will quit.
@endnode

@node "help_screen_force" "Force screen requester size"
This option will tell to forget columns/lines definations and use directly
screen requesters pixel size for custom screen. I suggest to use this with
custom screen, in public screen this option has no effect.
@endnode

@node "help_transfer" "Transfer"

                    @{"                Transfer                 " link "help_emulation" 0}

                    +---------------------------------------+
                    |@{"                                       " link "help_transfer_lv" 0}|
                    |                                       |
                    +---------------------------------------+
                    @{"Upload path" link "help_transfer_upload_path" 0} --- @{"X" link "help_transfer_automatical_up_d" 0} @{"Automatical up/download" link "help_transfer_automatical_up_d" 0}
                    @{"Dnload path" link "help_transfer_dnload_path" 0} --- @{"X" link "help_transfer_minimal_status_d" 0} @{"Minimal status display " link "help_transfer_minimal_status_d" 0}
                    @{"Dnload list" link "help_transfer_dnload_list" 0} --- @{"X" link "help_transfer_double_buffer" 0} @{"Double buffer          " link "help_transfer_double_buffer" 0}
@endnode

@node "help_transfer_lv" ""
Which protocol to use.

Note: @{"Explanation why pick from profile don't work." link "help_screen_lv" 0}
@endnode

@node "help_transfer_upload_path" "Upload path"

@endnode

@node "help_transfer_dnload_path" "Download path"

@endnode

@node "help_transfer_dnload_list" "Download list"

@endnode

@node "help_transfer_automatical_up_d" "Automatic protocol start"
Check incoming data for those magic upload/download strings and start current
protocol if they are received.
@endnode

@node "help_transfer_minimal_status_d" "Minimal status display"
Do not open file transfer window but instead show transfer status in status
line. Note that this will be extremely confusing if you don't have status line
on.
@endnode

@node "help_transfer_double_buffer" "Double buffer"
Use double buffered send in xpr protocols, this will allow much better upload
performance. This should be always on as all new protocols will work with it,
however very old protocols may not work as they need to be in sync at other
end. Fortunately those protocols are no longer practical as modern modems
don't get very good performance with them.
@endnode

@node "help_emulation" "Emulation"

                  @{"                 Emulation                 " link "help_keyboard" 0}

                  @{"                 Ansi/VT102                " link "doc_emulations" 0}
                  +--+ ==== Red ====  @{"X" link "help_emulation_line_wrap" 0} @{"Line wrap            " link "help_emulation_line_wrap" 0}
                  |  | ==== Green ==  @{"X" link "help_emulation_destructive_bac" 0} @{"Destructive backspace" link "help_emulation_destructive_bac" 0}
