@node "help_emulation_lf_to_cr_lf" "LF to CR/LF"

@endnode

@node "help_emulation_pc_ansi_16_colo" "PC Ansi (16 colors)"
Use 16 colors in ansi, this is widely used in bbs systems. Note that in public
screen you must have at least 16 free pens to this look perfect, and also in
custom screen you must use at least 32 colors screen if @{"Keep workbench colors" link "help_screen_keep_workbench_col" 0}
option is on.
@endnode

@node "help_emulation_prescroll" "Prescroll"
When this is non zero then received data is checked and simple scroll
prediction is made causing more or less jumpy scroll. As prediction method is
very simple it is possible that it can go wrong in some complex ansi data but
generally it works as intended. Bigger the value then more jumpy scroll can be
but only if DreamTerm can't print received data at same speed as it is
received. I suggest you to use maximum value for this if you don't have
graphics card as normal Amiga hardware is extremely slow in scrolling. Also it
is propably good idea to install CpuBlit or similar in machines like A1200 as
it will double the scrolling speed. Option is of course used only with
internal Ansi emulation, if that wasn't clear before. :)

And value is just maximum look ahead range for calculating lines, due that
very small values (<256) propably won't make much prescrolling.
@endnode

@node "help_keyboard" "Keyboard"

                    @{"               Keyboard                " link "help_modem" 0}

                    @{"F1" link "help_keyboard_function_keys" 0} ----------------  @{"F6" link "help_keyboard_function_keys" 0} ---------------
                    @{"F2" link "help_keyboard_function_keys" 0} ----------------  @{"F7" link "help_keyboard_function_keys" 0} ---------------
                    @{"F3" link "help_keyboard_function_keys" 0} ----------------  @{"F8" link "help_keyboard_function_keys" 0} ---------------
                    @{"F4" link "help_keyboard_function_keys" 0} ----------------  @{"F9" link "help_keyboard_function_keys" 0} ---------------
                    @{"F5" link "help_keyboard_function_keys" 0} ----------------  @{"F0" link "help_keyboard_function_keys" 0} ---------------
                    X @{"Convert cr to cr/lf" link "help_keyboard_convert_cr_to_cr" 0}
                    X @{"Convert lf to cr/lf" link "help_keyboard_convert_lf_to_cr" 0}
@endnode

@node "help_keyboard_function_keys" "Function keys"
You can define different string for every function key (f1-f10), that string
is of course sent to serial when you press particular function key.
@endnode

@node "help_keyboard_convert_cr_to_cr" "Convert cr to cr/lf"
Convert outcoming return (0x0d) to return/linefeed pair.
@endnode

@node "help_keyboard_convert_lf_to_cr" "Convert lf to cr/lf"
Convert outcoming linefeed to return/linefeed pair.
@endnode

@node "help_modem" "Modem"

                    @{"                 Modem                 " link "help_bbs" 0}

                    Dial prefix ------- Dial suffix -------
                    No Carrier  ------- No DialTone -------
                    Connect     ------- Ringing     -------
                    Error       ------- Busy        -------
                    Ok          ------- Hangup      -------
                    Dial abort  -------

Only dialer uses these strings, expect Hangup string is not used by dialer but
@{"Hangup action" link "menu_serial_hangup" 0}.
@endnode

@node "help_cs" "Charset configuration"
 Charset
  @{"Load            " link "help_base_general_load" 0}    +----------------------------+
  @{"Save            " link "help_base_general_save" 0}    |@{"                            " link "help_base_general_lv" 0}|
  @{"Append          " link "help_base_general_append" 0}    |                            |
  @{"Save selected   " link "help_base_general_save_selecte" 0}    |                            |
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~    |                            |
  @{"Close           " link "help_base_general_close" 0}    +----------------------------+
                      @{"X" link "help_cs_font" 0} ---- width ---- height -----
                      @{"   TXD (output) conversion    " link "help_cs_txd" 0}
                      @{"    RXD (input) conversion    " link "help_cs_rxd" 0}
                      @{"  Capture/review conversion   " link "help_cs_cap" 0}
                      @{"      Add      " link "help_base_general_add" 0} @{"    Delete    " link "help_base_general_delete" 0}

With this window you can create/edit character sets, one set contains a name,
font name & size, and three conversion tables. Name is used by entries for
select which charset to use, if entry is using charset which is not found from
list it will silently fall back to use ISO charset. Due this ISO charset
cannot be deleted/edited and is always present. However I suggest you not to
use it and instead create ISO.topaz etc. set so you can control it's
characterist. Set which is currently in use cannot be edited. Also bear in
mind that all changes are immediately on effect.
@endnode

@node "help_cs_font" "Font requester"
This will open font requester where you can choose which font to use, if you
choose so called 'native' Amiga font and use bbs system which uses ibm-font
you must also load right conversion table.
@endnode

@node "help_cs_txd" "TXD (output) conversion"
This will load new output conversion which is used when chars are sent from
DreamTerm to host. There are some menu commands (send noconv) which can pass
this to allow send of already converted text.

@{u} How to make conversion file? @{uu}

Prepare 256 bytes long index file which is used like this:

Char x is converted to char index[x], if index[x] is zero then char is
stripped. Can it be any simpler?
@endnode

@node "help_cs_rxd" "RXD (input) conversion"
This will load conversion table which is used for received chars which are
printed to console.  Conversion is not needed if font is already right, for
example SF8 uses DT_IBM01 font which is 8-bit finnish set and thus @{b}do not@{ub} @{b}need@{ub}
that received ibm-chars are converted. If XEm emulation is selected then this
conversion is disabled.

@{u} How to make conversion table? @{uu}

Prepare 256 bytes long index file which is used like this:

Char x is converted to char index[x], if index[x] is zero then char is
stripped. Can it be any simpler?
@endnode

@node "help_cs_cap" "Capture/review conversion"
This will load conversion which is used for Review/Capture data, useful if you
for example use IBM in bbs and want your capture & review to be iso-latin
which Amiga uses. Note that supplied tables will strip return ($d) and some
controls, this is required for review to look ok. As old charset configuration
did not have this all charsets created with versions 1.0 to 1.3 will use
noconversion in this before you change it.

@{u} How to make conversion table? @{uu}

Prepare 256 bytes long index file which is used like this:

Char x is converted to char index[x], if index[x] is zero then char is
stripped. Can it be any simpler?
@endnode

@node "help_xp" "Protocol configuration"
 Protocol
  @{"Load            " link "help_base_general_load" 0}    +-----------------------------------+
  @{"Save            " link "help_base_general_save" 0}    |@{"                                   " link "help_base_general_lv" 0}|
  @{"Append          " link "help_base_general_append" 0}    |                                   |
  @{"Save selected   " link "help_base_general_save_selecte" 0}    |                                   |
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~    |                                   |
  @{"Close           " link "help_base_general_close" 0}    +-----------------------------------+
                      @{"      Xpr 2.001         External     " link "help_xp_type" 0}
                      @{"Xpr library  " link "help_xp_xpr_library" 0} @{"X" link "help_xp_xpr_library" 0} -- @{"DOS Upload   " link "help_xp_dos_upload" 0} @{"X" link "help_xp_dos_upload" 0} --
                      @{"Init string  " link "help_xp_init_string" 0} @{"X" link "help_xp_init_string" 0} -- @{"DOS Download " link "help_xp_dos_download" 0} @{"X" link "help_xp_dos_download" 0} --
                      @{"Auto upload  " link "help_xp_auto_upload" 0} ---- @{"Auto upload  " link "help_xp_auto_upload" 0} ----
                      @{"Auto download" link "help_xp_auto_dnload" 0} ---- @{"Auto download" link "help_xp_auto_dnload" 0} ----
                      @{"       Add        " link "help_base_general_add" 0} @{"      Delete      " link "help_base_general_delete" 0}

With this window you can create/edit protocols, one protocol contains a name,
library name, initstring DOS upload, DOS download and auto upload/download
Name is used by phonebook entries for selecting which protocol to use, if
entry is using protocol which is not found from list it will silently stop
using it. Protocol entry which is currently in use cannot be edited. Also bear
in mind that all changes are immediately on effect.
@endnode

@node "help_xp_type" "Type"
Selects which protocol driver type to use, there is currently two:

Xpr 2.001

Uses external xpr#?.libraries.

External

Runs external program which is supposed to handle transfer, however there is
some things which must be taken on account. First if you use hardware serial
you must disable DTR checking in modem, otherwise modem will hangup as soon
you start protocol, this condition is also true if you don't use shared
serial. If you use normal serial.device or any other alternative then you
should use shared serial option on as it will make possible to run external
program without freeing serial.device, in fact there is same procedure as done
when using @{"serial active" link "menu_serial_serial active" 0} menu. Second you must propably pass some information
to that standalone protocol, see string codes which can be inserted here (or
any dreamterm string in fact).

Now for some other things, as during transfer DreamTerm cannot know in which
state modem is your so called 'online' condition will remain true and
unchecked until you quit that external program, it is checked rigth after it
stops and if carrier is not on you will immediately go offline (meaning that
standard 'terminating connection' procedures are done).

Note: In fact there would be no need to use external protocols as XPr 2.001 is
able to handle bi-directional transfers, however I can see that this way of
handling things has advantaces. Like that DModem is useless crap and only one
which actually uses XPr 2.001. :-)
@endnode

@node "help_xp_xpr_library" "XPr library"
This will open file requester where you can choose which xpr library to use,
there is no check if library really is xpr library so be careful.  Library can
be loaded anywhere put I suggest you to use libs: as then libraries are shared
with other applications.
@endnode

@node "help_xp_init_string" "Init string"
If xpr library supports interactive setting this will pop up somekind of
window where you can change xpr library settings, if not you must type
initstring manually. Note that you must first select xpr library if you want
this to work.
@endnode

@node "help_xp_auto_upload" "Automatic upload"
When this string is detected in input stream then DreamTerm will start
uploading with this protocol. Note that only protocol which is currently
active is checked against this magic string.

Note: You must not use XPr libraries own options to make automatic start, they
are not supported.
@endnode

@node "help_xp_auto_dnload" "Automatic download"
When this string is detected in input stream then DreamTerm will start
downloading with this protocol. Note that only protocol which is currently
active is checked against this magic string.

Note: You must not use XPr libraries own options to make automatic start, they
are not supported.
@endnode

@node "help_xp_dos_upload" "DOS upload"
Command string to start external program for uploading, use same string as you
would use in Shell. For best result you propably have to use those cryptics
@{"string codes" link "doc_string commands" 0}, note that if you supply paths you must use " around it. Shortly:
no %ru but "%ru"
@endnode

@node "help_xp_dos_download" "DOS download"
Command string to start external program for downloading, use same string as
you would use from Shell. For best result you propably have to use those
cryptics @{"string codes" link "doc_string commands" 0}, note that if you supply paths you must use " around it.
Shortly: no %rd but "%rd"
@endnode

@node "help_xm" "XEm 2.0 configuration"
 External emulations
  @{"Load            " link "help_base_general_load" 0}    +----------------+
  @{"Save            " link "help_base_general_save" 0}    |@{"                " link "help_base_general_lv" 0}|
  @{"Append          " link "help_base_general_append" 0}    |                |
  @{"Save selected   " link "help_base_general_save_selecte" 0}    |                |
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~    |                |
  @{"Close           " link "help_base_general_close" 0}    +----------------+
                      ------------------   @{"Colors to use" link "help_xm_colors_to_use" 0} ======
                      @{"XEm library" link "help_xm_xem_library" 0} @{"X" link "help_xm_xem_library" 0} ----   @{"Change options" link "help_xm_change_options" 0} @{"Reset" link "help_xm_reset" 0}
                      @{"         Add        " link "help_base_general_add" 0} @{"       Delete       " link "help_base_general_delete" 0}

With this window you can create/edit emulations, one emulation contains a
name, colors, library and options. Name is used by phonebook entries for
selecting which emulation to use, if entry is using emulation which is not
found from list it will silently fall back to use ANSI/VT102. Emulation which
is currently in use cannot be edited. Also bear in mind that all changes are
immediately on effect.
@endnode

@node "help_xm_xem_library" "XEm library"
This will open file requester where you can choose which xem library to use,
there is no check if library really is xem library so be careful.  Library can
be loaded anywhere put I suggest you to use libs: as then libraries are shared
with other applications. You also cannot use Change options or Reset before
this is valid.
@endnode

@node "help_xm_colors_to_use" "Colors to use"
Use this to set how many colors XEm library really uses, this should be 2,4,8
or 16 as XEm interface has only screen depth. Note however that colors are
used only in custom screen.
@endnode

@node "help_xm_change_options" "Change options"
This will open somekind of window where you can change xem library settings,
you must have valid library in @{"XEm library" link "help_xm_xem library" 0} for this to work.
@endnode

@node "help_xm_reset" "Reset"
This will reset xem library to its internal defaults. If you have changed
library version you should reset its configuration and then change settings.
@endnode

@node "help_tb" "Toolbar configuration"
 Toolbars
  @{"Load            " link "help_base_general_load" 0}    +---+ +--------------+
  @{"Save            " link "help_base_general_save" 0}    |@{"   " link "help_base_general_lv" 0}| |@{" Button image " link "help_tb_image" 0}|
  @{"Append          " link "help_base_general_append" 0}    |   | +--------------+
  @{"Save selected   " link "help_base_general_save_selecte" 0}    |   | Format  
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~    |   | @{"Serial " link "help_tb_serial" 0} --------
  @{"Close           " link "help_base_general_close" 0}    |   | @{"Command" link "help_tb_command" 0} --------
                      |   | @{"     Action     " link "help_tb_action" 0}
                      |   | ================
                      +---+   Add    Delete
                  
                      @{"    Add    " link "help_base_general_add" 0} @{"  Delete  " link "help_base_general_delete" 0} 

With this window you can create/edit toolbars, one toolbar contains an
unlimited number of graphics buttons which each can have serial string, dos
command and internal action. Toolbar which is currently in use cannot be
edited. Also bear in mind that all changes are immediately on effect.
@endnode

@node "help_tb_image" "Button image"
Pressing this you can select which image to use, you can select any format
which datatypes support. Only file name and path is stored in configuration so
possible changes in file will also change button image. All images in one
toolbar should be same size as layout will look ugly otherwise. So if you plan
to use vertical bar then at least heights should be same and in horizontal bar
widths, however this is not required for maximum flexibility. Also image sizes
shouldn't be too big as MUI is not very fast in remapping images for current
screen colors. Also keep in mind screen limitations when creating bars, if you
use many buttons all of them may not fit in one row as you may want.

Note: As image colors are remapped to current screen they will be different in
other screen configurations or when all buttons are shown at once. I recommend
to use same palette for every button for best results if you use low screen
depth. Also if screen has no free pens left then remapping may give really
strange results if colors differs greatly, due that you should use at least 32
color screens when using toolbars. Or you can find some buttons which use same
colors as in emulation uses.

Bugs in datatypes: Some datatypes seems to be limited and do not support all
methods how to layout image, this may lead to strange looking images. Can also
be bug in my datatype loader...
@endnode

@node "help_tb_serial" "Serial"
This string is sent to serial when you button is pressed.
@endnode

@node "help_tb_command" "Command"
This DOS command is executed when button is pressed.
@endnode

@node "help_tb_action" "Action"
This internal DreamTerm action is done when button is pressed.
@endnode

@node "help_cr" "Crypting options"

                         @{"Library " link "help_cr_library" 0} -------------------
                         @{"Password" link "help_cr_password" 0} -------------------
@endnode

@node "help_cr_library" "Library"
Which xpk library to use crypt phonebook, you need also version 2 of xpkmaster
library. Because this is not used often I decided not to code nice looking
automatic interface. Just enter xpk packer id string which is constructed this
way: xxxx.yyy, where xxxx is id and yyy is packmode (IDEA.100 is good choice).
@endnode

@node "help_cr_password" "Password"
Which password to use in conjuction with xpk library, enter some hard to quess
phrase as it is more secure than one individual word. This will be asked next
time you start DreamTerm and if you cannot remember it then your phonebook is
lost forever, entered password will be shown here so do not open crypting
options window if somebody is looking over your shoulder.
@endnode

@node "help_di" "Dialer"

@endnode

@node "help_fi" "Upload list"

@endnode

@node "help_rv" "Review"
 Review
 @{" Save         " link "help_rv_save" 0}

Note that in @{"charset configuration" link "help_cs" 0} there is @{"conversion table for review" link "help_cs_cap" 0} too,
you must always use table which converts data to ISO and strips all control
codes ($d for example) from it. 

For controlling review use either mouse and sliders or keyboard, however
currently you must press tab once when you open review window in order
keyboard control to work. When scrolling left/right whole window is redrawn,
that is only because review font can be proportional.
@endnode

@node "help_rv_save" "Save"

@endnode

